  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>CHAPTER 7: THE JOURNEY</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>-----</p>
<font size="+3">Chapter 7: The Journey</font>
<p>-----</p>
<p>Lenia awoke to find herself alone.   Wondering where Ravell had gone, she left the room and began to search the inn.  She walked the hallways, hoping she wouldn't have to enter any rooms.  She finally came across the balcony of the inn, which overlooked the white temple of Marr.  Ravell's arms were folded across the wooden rails as he stared at the sky above the temple.</p>
<p>"You're up early.  What are you doing out here." Lenia asked.</p>
<p>Ravell turned his gaze down towards the temple.  "I was just watching the sunrise.  I've never seen it."</p>
<p>Lenia walked over and stood next to him.  "I can't imagine what it's like to have missed so much of Tunare's beauty."</p>
<p>"Even the faerie fires in Neriak don't hold as many colors as the sunrise."Ravell replied.</p>
<p>Lenia looked at Ravell curiously. "Well then, here we are.  Alone in this city with no real place to go.  Any ideas?"</p>
<p>Ravell was quiet for a few moments before speaking. "I know exactly where we can go.  Where we <i>need</i> to go."</p>
<p>"Go on." Lenia detected the note of worry in Ravell's voice.</p>
<p>"I wanted to tell your brother about this, but he is gone.  The elven city of Kelethin is in danger, and Felwithe is their next target after that." Ravell sounded like he only half wanted to share this.</p>
<p>At the mention of her hometown, Lenia became worried.  "What do you mean?  What kind of danger?!</p>
<p>Ravell finally turned to look Lenia in the eyes.  "There are drow on Faydwer.  They are allied with the Crushbone Orcs.  I don't know where they are or when they will attack, but I know that they plan to destroy the elves, and after they are gone, the orcs."</p>
<p>Lenia now plainly looked ill.  "How do you know all of this? Surely you must be mistaken.  The elves, gnomes, or even dwarves would have noticed if there were drow on our continent."</p>
<p>"No, as unbelievable as it may sound, the drow are quite capable of doing this.  I heard this because I was a member of an elite band of drow.  Our master had every intention of training us and sending us to join the others in Faydwer.  Your home is in danger, don't question me about how or why Lenia.  Just know that there is a plain threat to your way of life, and I want to get rid of it." Ravell continued to look Lenia directly in the eyes as he emphasized the danger her home was in.</p>
<p>Lenia took a moment to collect herself before replying. "If what you say is true...then my father can help.  He carries a lot of influence around Felwithe."</p>
<p>Ravell nodded.  "I thought you had the look of noble blood about you.  We need to go immediately."</p>
<p>"We?  You can't go, Ravell.  If you are seen you will be killed, especially around Felwithe.  No, you need to stay somewhere safe while I go handle this." Lenia warned.</p>
<p>"Don't worry about me.  Lenia, I'm going to Faydwer.  You can't stop me, so just help me instead." Ravell grinned.</p>
<p>Lenia mumbled something about men before walking off and motioning for Ravell to follow.</p>
<p>-----</p>
<p>"Lord N'Vitar, I'm sorry but I must postpone my training.  There's personal business to take care of."Lilith kneeled before a dark throne holding a leather-faced old drow in robes.</p>
<p>The old figure's eyes were like a hawk's, and despite his age he still managed to throw an oppressive glare at the shadowknight before him.  "You are talking about the renegade.  Listen to me, you will not pursue this fool any longer.  I have dispatched assassins to take care of him.  You have promise, young knight.  You will bring great hatred upon the world, but you first must train!  Do not forsake your training for some idiot rebel, or you will be sorry."</p>
<p>Lilith held her tongue, but barely.  "Aye sir, as you wish.  May I ask one favor, then?"</p>
<p>"That depends upon the favor." N'Vitar's eyebrow raised.</p>
<p>"When your assassins find him,"Lilith grinned.  "Have them bring him back here so that I may take his soul to torture for all eternity."</p>
<p>The old drow laughed slightly.  "That I shall do for you."</p>
<p>Lilith's grin widened.  "Thank you, I shall go train now."</p>
<p>As the shadowknight left the room, N'Vitar's eyes followed her.  "I have found a use for that rebel.  I shall use him to feed her hatred, and someday she shall be a paragon of hate and fear." He thought to himself.</p>
<p>-----</p>
<p>"I will have to jump off of here early, you know.  I very much doubt they'll like me trying to get off at the docks of Faydwer." Ravell remarked.</p>
<p>Lenia watched as the boat sailed through the waters and around islands, and the wind danced her hair about.  "I'll tell you when to jump."</p>
<p>"I really don't like this," Ravell suddenly looked ill. "These boats are something I don't want to get used to."</p>
<p>Lenia just laughed as the drow ran and lurched over the railing.  The boat continued its way, cutting through the water.  After some time, Lenia noticed the continent of Faydwer approaching from the distance.  "Ravell, that's Faydwer.  Jump when we get close, but don't wait for the docks to sneak up on you."</p>
<p>Ravell nodded and perched himself at the edge of the boat, ready to jump.  The waters running by made him want to share his breakfast with the waters again, but he held it back.  When he saw the walls of Butcherblock's docking area approaching, Ravell jumped into the waters.  He struggled for a moment or two before he managed to swim clumsily to the shore. "Now," Ravell stood and shook the water out of his clothes.  "Here comes the hard part."</p>
<p>-----</p> </font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><small>By <b>Ravell</b> Submited on 7/14/2001</small></td>
